<br>
The assembly met in the great hall nearly an hour later, the rustling of robes and the screeching of wooden chair legs scraping the floor the only sounds made, as they all seated themselves in front of the platform.<br>
<br>
Brother McHearn strode in carrying a freshly washed bundle and made his way to the platform.  Setting the bundle down on a podium erected for any theological dissertation, he pulled out a white-washed plank and a charcoal pencil and began to scribble..<br>
<br>
“I am sure you all have questions and hopefully, I can answer them with God’s help.  We have a situation here unheard of in the history of this Monastery.” (Hey! It’s a BIG plank..)  He held it up over his head and watched everyone nod when they were done reading.  He took a rag, wiped it down, and again began scribbling.<br>
<br>
“In my studies this morning I heard a wailing from the field, and BEHOLD! I found this!” he held the sign up quickly, and set it back down, picking up the baby and holding it above his head.  A friar in the back row picked up a board from under his seat and began scribbling furiously, he held up his sign and Brother McHearn squinted at it;<br>
<br>
“…… ……… …   …… .. ..”<br>
<br>
Sighing, McHearn put the baby down and erased his own board and wrote,<br>
“What?? I can’t hear you from here.”<br>
<br>
The other friar erased his board and wrote even larger;<br>
“I wasn’t done reading”<br>
<br>
After squinting for what seemed a short eternity, Brother McHearn nodded and  started scribbling on his own board;<br>
“I said, My studies were interrupted.. Bah!” and held it over his head again, clearly frustrated.<br>
<br>
“No more silence for a quarter of an hour!  It’s a baby!”  the sound of his voice went across the assembly gathered and hit them like thunder.  He broke the uncomfortable silence with unethical behavior then proceeded to lift the baby again over his head knocking the plank from it’s precarious perch on the pedestal (try saying that 5 times fast) to the floor with a resounding clatter, which in turn, awoke the sleeping baby who started it’s wailing anew!<br>
<br>
Chaos came to the sanctuary and made itself comfy in the grand hall with the friars assembled there.  Voices unused for years began to speak out and what resulted was a cacophony of tumultuous noise that could wake the dead, which they later decided would be a much easier way to perform resurrections.  Chaos’ only complaint?  Not enough color.. Brown robes were so unfashionable now a days.<br>
