<br>
Deep within the monasteries library lay a piece of worn parchment rolled tight into a scroll.  It had been there ever since the monastery was built in 72 A.D.  Contained in the scroll was a prophecy.  The first translation of this scroll hung in the great hall over the dias to remind them of the higher purpose they were all to take part in.  Every brother in the abbey had committed this prophecy to memory as it helped them to maintain their faith knowing the Lord was sending them help.  It was their first duty upon entering the ranks of friar, or acolyte.  It was a cornerstone of their daily life.  They often stopped to gaze upon it again and again during daily meditation,  It fulfilled them and gave them a little insight into the Maker’s Divine Plan.<br>
<br>
It read:<br>
“And He shall come from the swine, covered in offal.  And ye shall name him in honor of the Water walking disciple, and He shall bring light into Camelot, yea’ even to the ends of all Avalon.  And ere’ His arrival, and the great Revival that will surge forth, ye’ shall all live reminding one another to be celibate, in honor of all the Lord is given’ ye’.”<br>
<br>
A short prophecy, but clearly stated, and none had ever doubted it’s great importance.  It was clear.  This was the child spoken about in the instructive words.  This was the child of prophecy, and the Lord had finally seen fit to place Him in their care.  They decided then at that assembly to raise him up in the ways of a friar, and to award him the name:<br>
Simon Peter.<br>
<br>
*Later that eve Brother Hearn strode about the halls of the abbey and made his way down to the library, his favorite place to spend time in prayer with his Father.  He decided to carefully search out the original scroll (being one of the only people that could still read the original archaic) and to hold it and read it reverently.  He enjoyed times like this.  His whole life had been dedicated towards the preparation of what was now here.<br>
<br>
Pulling the scroll down from a shelf in the back he blew the dust off it’s surface.  The parchment itself had grown brittle and thin.  He held it lovingly, as he would a tankard of fine ale (he IS a friar after all.) and cradled it close to him.  Moving underneath the glow of a oil lantern, he read each word slowly, one at a time a broad smile on his face, and the love of God in his heart..<br>
<br>
Hours later, the sound of Brother Hearn weeping could still be heard if one went close enough to the library.  He continued to sob through the night and kept gazing upon the last line of the prophecy through puffy, red, tear filled eyes..<br>
<br>
“And ere’ His arrival, and the great Revival that will surge forth, ye’ shall all live reminding one another to CELEBRATE, in honor of all the Lord is given’ ye’.”<br>
