<br>
“The young lad grew,<br>
as young lads do,<br>
Becoming a man,<br>
Of fifteen hands span!<br>
And strong as a ox,<br>
With a huge, giant co---“ The singsong voice abruptly stopped as the staff came across the back of his head.  The young acolytes gathered, gasped at the actions of the seemingly ancient friar. <br>
Brother McHearn placed his staff back on the wall behind him and shook his head solemnly as he called healing blessings down on the flamboyantly adorned and recently rendered unconscious minstrel.  ‘Why’ he thought to himself ‘must those of the story tellin’ art be forever cursed to moments of stupidity?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I shall be’ tellin’ the story of young Simon Peter’s growth myself then!” he declared casting one last disgusted look at the minstrel.  Since he was at the Diocese Recruitment Academy Boarding house (or D.R.A.B.) as he was so fond of thinking of it, the laws of silence didn’t stand here.<br>
He began the story;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “You see, we had no idea how to raise this young pup of a Briton.  For two days he cried and hollered and screamed as we tried to find a way to keep em’ fed.  We had been drippin’ milk into his maw but it seemed it was never enough fer’ young Simon, he was a hungry boy indeed!  Just when we thought he may waste away, Brother Taylor came up with an idea that none of us dimwits had thought of afore’.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He took one of his thickly woven gloves and cut a small slit into the end of it and filled it with lambs milk he did!  The glove would then feed it slowly into the mouth of the babe. It was ingenious!  The glove has since been a church relic and cast in gold, and in honor, Brother Taylor received a “Golden Glove Award” for having the deep insight to feed God’s chosen one..”<br>
As Brother McHearn continued he found himself recalling the memories vividly and it all played out in a picture in his mind.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The days of Simon’s infancy to the earliest years of his study in the Theology and the art of Staff wielding.  Years passed in his minds eye to that time and he recounted the time.  Simon proved to be a extremely fast learner in the ways of the written Word, but proved less than desirable in the art of self defense.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The sun shone down on the hillside between the Monastery and Humberton and caught in it’s rays two brown robed people walking slowly.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “You see Simon, the staff becomes an extension of your own person.  Think of it as part of you.  Be the staff Simon, be the Staff!”  he pointed down the jade colored hillside to a black wolf cub.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “See that beasty there Lad?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Simon’s blonde hair shook uncontrollably as he nodded an affirmative to the elder friar, and threw a lopsided grin McHearns way.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Go and smite it!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The boy looked up at him perplexed. “Smite it Sir?” he asked.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Yes boy!” the friar responded turning his own staff about it figure eights and bludgeoning the air about him wickedly. “Like that, go forth and smite it!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Well.. Ok..” Simon, now a lad of 8 years, took up his staff uncertainly and began down the hillside towards the rather large and vicious wolf.  On the way down his imagination built a fiendish image in his mind.  Snarling and growling the wolf looked at him hungrily and raised its hackles towards him threateningly, long strands of saliva dripping from it’s blood soaked jaws.  He looked at the pup a moment before he ran back up to the elder friar.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “But Sir.. He’s dangerous!  He’d make a meal out of me!” the boy protested, looking frightened for his young life.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Brother McHearn blinked looking at the little wolf pup sitting calmly on it’s haunches licking it’s paw.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Um.. Yes, I suppose he COULD be dangerous, but I am here to offer thee my protection.  Now go forth and commence with the smitage!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Simon now disheartened trudged back down the hillside until he came within only feet of his dreaded enemy.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The Friar watched his young charge approach the young pup who stood up playfully panting at the lads arrival.  But that’s not how Simon saw it;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The black wolf again became aware of his attackers presence and growled low and gnashed it’s wicked fangs in the air.  It’s red eyes stared deep into Simon’s soul, and the boy new fear, true fear.  He raised his staff behind his head in a basic stance and proceded to strike forth at the wolf.  His first swing flew high and he decided to try the figure eight manuvere.  Closing the distance between himself and the mortal foe in front of him he swung the staff around with all his might and connected!  With his forehead!<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Dazed and stunned the boy knew he had erred and the enemy would soon be upon him.  He cried out for help and felt the pups talons dig into his shoulders and it’s weight press upon him.  The last thing he felt was the heat of the rancid breath of the foul creature on his cheek as he slipped into unconciousness and dreamed of being eaten alive.  He cried out in his recent sleep.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Help, he eating me.. he’s eating.. me..”  the prone form made a bunch of gurgling noises as Brother McHearn ran to his side.   Simon was in trouble indeed!  The young wolf was nearly licking him to death.  Barely containing a chuckle, the Father lifted the young puppy off his protégé and shoo’d him away.  He knelt by Simon and shook him back to awareness.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “What happened.. Did I win?” as Simon sat up blood rushed from the fresh cut on his head into his eye.  He realized then all his mortal wounds were real and he was dying.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I’m.. “ he gasped for his last breath “Dying.. I’m sorry Father!”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Yer’ not dyin’ Lad!” the friar exclaimed as he pulled a long wicked splinter from the boys forehead “at worst, ye’d have administered yourself a “staff infection.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp McHearn briefly spoke words of healing over his pupil and they headed back to the Monastery. And back to the vow of silence. <br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “And that lads, is where the great Simon Peter found himself at your very age.  So, do you wish this life of the monastery for yer’self?  If you’re destined to follow in his footsteps, then accompany me back.  Get yer’ things together and let’s get moving.”  He wrapped up his story and several of the young friars made haste to round up their things.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He prayed silently.. O’ Lord give me the strength…<br>
